Hit Probabilities & Valuing Hitters¶

In this installment of baseball research, I'm going to try fitting some different machine learning algorithms to predict the outcome of a batted ball based on things like its speed and trajectory. I'll test their accuracy and ultimately settle on a most effective model.

Modern Player Evaluation¶

One of the biggest revolutions in baseball analysis has been shifting away from measuring player success on the outcome of plays and instead on things they have control over. When a hitter is up to the plate, one of the biggest things he's responsible for is hitting the ball hard and at a favorable trajectory.

I'm going to use a hitter's batted-ball data to try to uncover their true talent. That is, trying to predict what should have happened based only on the hitter's contributions -- how hard they hit the ball and where.

Model Building¶

My goal here isn't necessarily to predict the outcome of a hit as accurately as possible. I'm intentionally leaving out features that would provide context, like the stadium, the fielding team, or the relevant fielder, because the batter has no control over them. I'll try the more descriptive model in another writeup.

If we're trying to uncover a player's true talent, we'd build our models using only the things the player is responsible for:

  • batted ball speed
  • batted ball vertical angle (launch angle)
  • batted ball horizontal angle (direction/spray angle)
  • batter handedness

I mostly care about the probabilistic predictions from each model. I can get the classification from that data, but more importantly, those probabilities are useful. If we assign a value to the results of a batted ball, we can calculate the expected value of the batted ball and use that to value a hitter.

Before I start with any models, I actually need to calculate the batted ball direction myself.

Calculating horizontal launch angle¶

Statcast directly provides the batted ball speed and vertical launch angle, but doesn't exactly give the horizontal launch angle. What it does give is the hc_x and hc_y, which correspond to the x and y coordinate positions where the ball either landed or was fielded. We can calculate the horizontal angle at which the ball was hit from that. Let's check out what that data looks like.

Huh. So, it turns out hc_x and hc_y aren't centered with (0,0) at home plate, nor are they in units of feet. According to this document, they're defined as

Coordinates entered by operator in pressbox of where the ball is fielded. Based on 250x250 field graphic, where 0,0 is in the upper left corner, in very deep left field, and 250,250 is in the lower right corner, in foul territory between 1B and home plate. The fields are centered in that space, the x=125 axis runs through the middle of 2B, the pitchers mound and home plate; the 1B and 3B bases are roughly aligned on the y=175 line.

Ok, fine. So we'll transform it into normal coordinate system. The x-coordinate is easy enough to transform, we'll just subtract 125 from each entry. The y-coordinates will take a little more work. I'm going to use a little trick -- on balls hit straight up the middle of the field (x=125), the batted ball distance should be equal to the y-coordinate distance.

If we fit a linear regression between the hit distance and the y-coordinate for balls where x=125, then we'll be able to zero-out the y coordinate and get the transformation from pixel units to feet.

One thing to check -- The document above says hit_distance_sc measures the distance traveled by the ball, and hc_x and hc_y measure distance until the ball was fielded. On groundballs, hit_distance_sc might report a distance right in front of home plate and hc_x and hc_y might report a distance somewhere in the infield.

I'll just plot hc_y against hit_distance_sc with the hit type and see what's what.

Yep, so that's actually a problem. Ground balls and some line drives have further registered distances by hc_y (it's confusing, lower numbers are further) than the hit_distance_sc. All this means is that I'll just filter out ground balls and line drives when we regress hc_y and hit_distance_sc.

In [49]:
df_adj = df.copy(deep=True)

df_adj['hc_x'] = df_adj.hc_x - 125  # zero hc_x

# get non ground-balls and line-drives hit up the middle
df_0 = df_adj[(df_adj.hc_x >= -1) & 
    (df_adj.hc_x <= 1) &
    (df_adj.bb_type != 'ground_ball') &
    (df_adj.bb_type != 'line_drive')]

df_0 = df_0.dropna(subset=['hit_distance_sc']).reset_index(drop=True)

X = df_0[['hit_distance_sc']]
y = df_0['hc_y']

y_mod = LinearRegression().fit(X, y)

print('y-coord translation = %0.3f' % y_mod.intercept_)
print('pixel-feet conversion factor = %0.3f' % y_mod.coef_[0])

# transform y-coords so home plate is at y=0 and larger = further
df_adj['hc_y'] = (-1 * df_adj['hc_y']) + y_mod.intercept_

# apply conversion from pixels to feet
df_adj['hc_x'] = df_adj['hc_x'] / abs(y_mod.coef_[0])
df_adj['hc_y'] = df_adj['hc_y'] / abs(y_mod.coef_[0])

# calculate the horizontal angle based on hc_x and hc_y
direction = []
for i in range(len(df_adj)):
    hcx = df_adj.hc_x.iloc[i]
    hcy = df_adj.hc_y.iloc[i]

    if (hcx>=0 and hcy>=0) | (hcx<0 and hcy>=0):
        dr = np.rad2deg(np.arctan(hcx / hcy))

    elif hcx>=0 and hcy<0:
        dr = np.rad2deg(np.arctan(abs(hcx / hcy))) + 90

    elif hcx<0 and hcy<0:
        dr = -np.rad2deg(np.arctan(hcx / hcy)) - 90

    else:
        dr = np.nan

    direction.append(dr)

df_adj['direction'] = direction

y-coord translation = 212.916
pixel-feet conversion factor = -0.452

Looking back at the first plot, this passes the eye test. The y-coord translation means home plate is located at about y=213, which matches up with that plot. We'll divide hc_x and hc_y by about 0.45 to convert to feet.

Let's remake that first plot to make sure we've successfully transformed the data, and I'll add another plot to make sure the direction angle makes sense.

Nice! We are ready to move on to testing some models.

Predicting hit outcomes¶

We don't need a whole lot of information for these models. We only have the four features I mentioned above, plus whatever the outcome is -- 5 total columns of data. There's a few adjustments we need to make:

1) Remove any bunts from the dataset, since those aren't real swings
2) Statcast describes the type of out (sacrifice fly, fielders choice, etc), so I'm gonna map any non-hit outcome to 'out'
3) One-hot encode batter handedness
4) Over-sampling imbalanced data

Also, we have a pretty massive dataset (500k points), so I'm going to sample a much smaller set of data to train and test the models.

In [57]:
# stand = handedness
cols = ['events', 'stand', 'launch_speed', 'launch_angle', 'direction'] 

# drop bunts
df_adj = df_adj[cols][~df_adj['events'].isin(
    ['sac_bunt', 'sac_bunt_double_play'])]  

# anything that's not a hit = out
df_adj.loc[~df_adj['events'].isin(
    ['single', 'double', 'triple', 'home_run']), 'events'] = 'out'

# one-hot encode handedness
df_adj = pd.concat([df_adj, pd.get_dummies(df_adj.stand)], axis=1)

# drop unecessary columns & rename to be a little clearer
df_adj = df_adj.drop(columns=['stand', 'L'])
df_adj = df_adj.rename(columns={'R': 'is_Right'})


























    




























Looking at the distribution of outcomes, it's pretty clear that we need to do something to balance the data. Outs are 3x as common as the next most frequent outcome. Imbalanced data like this can make it hard for our models to be able to recognize patterns that describe a minority class. I'm going to use SMOTE (synthetic minority oversampling technique) to balance the dataset. SMOTE is an oversampling technique that creates new data points for minority classes based on examples from the existing data.


Here's what SMOTE does to a sample of data.

I'm also using sklearn's built-in cross validating function to cross-validate each model 5 times. I'm going to use 5 metrics to evaluate the models, which together should give a good picture of the best overall model:


    

  • F1 score (weighted by instances of each label)
    • 

  • recall (weighted by label)
    • 

  • precision (weighted by label)
    • 

  • balanced accuracy (for imbalanced datasets)
    • 

  • log loss
    • 



For this exercise, I'm going to use mostly default settings for the classifiers. Once I pick the best model, I'll do some parameter tuning in another writeup.

# numeric columns to scale and center
to_scale = ['launch_speed', 'launch_angle', 'direction']

# scoring metrics
scoring = {
    'f1_weighted': 'f1_weighted',
    'accuracy': 'balanced_accuracy',
    'recall': make_scorer(recall_score, average='weighted'),
    'precision': make_scorer(precision_score, average='weighted', zero_division=0),
    'neg_log_loss': 'neg_log_loss'
    }

# define classifier models
classifiers = [
    LogisticRegression(multi_class='multinomial', solver='sag'),
    KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=50),
    SVC(kernel='rbf', probability=True),
    DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=5),
    RandomForestClassifier(max_depth=5),
    GradientBoostingClassifier(max_depth=3)
    ]

# classifier names
clf_names = [
    'Logistic Regression',
    'KNN',
    'SVM',
    'Decision Tree',
    'Random Forest',
    'Gradient Boosting'
    ]

# sample data for training & testing
s = df_adj.sample(n=75000).reset_index(drop=True)
s[to_scale] = StandardScaler().fit_transform(s[to_scale]) 

X = s[['launch_speed', 'launch_angle', 'direction', 'is_Right']]
y = s['events']

# set train/test split and oversample training data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.6)
X_train, y_train = imblearn.over_sampling.SMOTE().fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

# SMOTE increases dataset size -- resample to manageable size
s_smote = pd.concat([y_train, X_train], axis=1).sample(n=40000)
X_train = s_smote[['launch_speed', 'launch_angle', 'direction', 'is_Right']]
y_train = s_smote['events']


f1, acc, recall, precision, log_loss = [], [], [], [], []
for clf in classifiers:
    
    # returns metric scores for 5 fits of the model
    res = cross_validate(clf.fit(X_train, y_train), X_test, y_test,
                         cv=5, scoring=scoring)
    results = pd.DataFrame(res)
    
    # save average scores
    f1.append(np.mean(results.test_f1_weighted))
    acc.append(np.mean(results.test_accuracy))
    recall.append(np.mean(results.test_recall))
    precision.append(np.mean(results.test_precision))
    log_loss.append(np.mean(results.test_neg_log_loss))

eval_cols = [
    'models',
    'F1 Score',
    'Balanced Accuracy',
    'Recall',
    'Precision',
    'Neg Log Loss'
    ]

model_eval = pd.DataFrame(data=zip(clf_names, f1, acc, recall, precision, log_loss),
                          columns=eval_cols)

display(model_eval)

In the final shootout, the gradient boosting and KNN algorithms were almost neck-and-neck. However, the gradient boosting approach was the best overall in log loss, which is one of the more important metrics for me. Like I mentioned at the beginning, I want the probabilistic outcomes -- log loss considers the probabilistic predictions, not just whether the classification is right or wrong, which makes it an important metric here.


With that, it looks like the gradient boosting model is the way to go. I have a few follow-ups to this reports I'd like to do:
